e to other CPU's, you would need to make <br />&gt; sure that allocation is stable with a smp_wmb() before you update the <br />&gt; pointer to that allocation.<br /><br />Just to clarify a hopefully obvious issue..<br /><br />The assumption here is that you don't protect things with locking. Of <br />course, if all people accessing the new pointer always have the <br />appropriate lock, then memory ordering never matters, since the locks take <br />care of it.<br /><br />So _most_ allocators obviously don't need to do any smp_wmb() at all. But <br />the ones that expose things locklessly (where page tables are just one <br />example) need to worry.<br /><br />Again, this is yet another reason to not put things in the allocator. The <br />allocator cannot know, and shouldn't care. For all the exact same reasons <br />that the allocator cannot know and shouldn't care whether the ctor results <br />in a 'final' version or whether the allocator will do some final fixups.<br /><br />		Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
